  <h1>{frontmatter.title}</h1>

  <p>
    You open Amazon. You search "custom 3D printed bracket." Within seconds you have forty options, most of them under ten dollars, most of them shipping from overseas. You click the one with the best reviews, add it to your cart, and forget about it for two weeks.
  </p>

  <p>
    By the time it arrives, it is the wrong colour, the wrong tolerance, printed at 15% infill in the cheapest PLA available. It cracks the second you stress it. You leave a two-star review and order a different one. That one cracks too.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the Amazon 3D print experience. And it is costing you more than you think.
  </p>

  <h2>What You Are Actually Buying When You Order from Amazon</h2>

  <p>
    Amazon and Etsy listings for custom 3D prints are typically fulfilled by one of two models: a massive overseas print farm running thousands of printers with minimum wages and zero quality control, or a North American reseller drop-shipping from those same overseas farms with a markup and a branded box.
  </p>

  <p>
    Temu is the honest version of this. The product you see listed for $3.99 costs $0.40 to produce in a factory in Guangdong province. The shipping is subsidized by Chinese government trade policy designed to undercut local manufacturers. You are not getting a deal. You are participating in a race to the bottom that is actively destroying local manufacturing capacity in Canada and the United States.
  </p>

  <p>
    The math is not complicated. When you spend $12 on a 3D-printed part from an overseas Amazon seller, approximately $0 of that stays in Canada. The Amazon cut goes to Seattle. The product cost goes overseas. The shipping subsidy is absorbed by Chinese state policy. Your $12 is gone from your local economy permanently.
  </p>

  <h2>What Local Manufacturing Actually Costs — and What You Get</h2>

  <p>
    A local maker in Atlantic Canada charges more. That is true. A custom bracket that costs $8 on Amazon might cost $18 from a local shop. Here is what that $18 actually buys you.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>It buys you the right material for your application.</strong> A local maker will ask you what the part is for. If it is going outside, they will print it in ASA. If it is going in an engine bay, they will suggest PETG or ABS. If it is structural, they will run it at 40-50% gyroid infill with proper wall counts. Amazon does not ask. Temu does not ask. They print everything in the same generic PLA at the lowest settings that will hold together long enough to clear the return window.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>It buys you correct tolerances.</strong> A local maker measures. They test fit. They iterate. When you need a part that fits a specific mounting hole pattern or seats against an existing component, the tolerance is the entire job. Overseas print farms print to a template, not to your actual hardware.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>It buys you accountability.</strong> If the part fails, you can talk to a person. A real person who knows what they printed, what material they used, what settings they ran. That person will reprint it, no questions. Try that with an Etsy reseller who is drop-shipping from Shenzhen.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>It buys you speed when it actually matters.</strong> Overseas shipping takes two to four weeks on a good day. A local maker ships within 24 to 48 hours. When your boat has a broken winch component and you leave on a passage in three days, local is the only option that exists.
  </p>

  <h2>The Hidden Cost of Cheap Parts</h2>

  <p>
    Consider the total cost of ownership, not the sticker price. You spend $8 on an Amazon part. It fails in six weeks. You spend another $8. That one fails in three weeks. Now you are at $16 and still without a working solution. You are also out four to eight weeks of calendar time waiting for shipping.
  </p>

  <p>
    A local $18 part printed in the correct material at correct settings will last years. You paid $18. You are done. The total cost of ownership math is not close.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the calculation most people never run because the sticker price feels obvious and the downstream costs are invisible until they are not.
  </p>

  <h2>Why Buying Local Is an Act of Economic Self-Defense</h2>

  <p>
    Atlantic Canada has been losing manufacturing capacity for forty years. Mills closed. Plants shuttered. Young people left for Toronto or Calgary because there were no technical jobs. What replaced them? Retail jobs selling products made elsewhere. Service jobs supporting supply chains that run through elsewhere.
  </p>

  <p>
    Distributed 3D printing is one of the few manufacturing sectors where the capital costs are low enough for local operators to compete. A motivated maker in Moncton with three printers and a good workflow can produce quality parts at competitive prices. They can build a small business. They can hire, eventually. They can train the next person.
  </p>

  <p>
    But only if there is demand. And demand means people choosing local over Amazon when local is a viable option.
  </p>

  <p>
    Every $18 you spend with a local maker instead of $8 with an overseas Amazon reseller keeps roughly $15 in the local economy after accounting for materials, equipment wear, and the maker's time. Over a year of regular orders, across a community of buyers, that adds up to real local economic activity. Wages paid locally. Rent paid locally. Materials sourced locally when possible.
  </p>

  <h2>What Temu Is Actually Doing to Local Manufacturing</h2>

  <p>
    Temu's business model is worth understanding clearly. The company is owned by PDD Holdings, a Chinese conglomerate. Their pricing model relies on two structural advantages that Canadian manufacturers cannot replicate: ultra-low labour costs in Chinese manufacturing hubs, and the Section 321 de minimis exemption in the United States (and equivalent policies in Canada) that allows low-value imports to bypass normal customs and duty collection.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not competition. This is subsidized displacement. When a Canadian manufacturer competes with Temu, they are competing against a company whose supply chain is propped up by trade policy arbitrage and wages that would be illegal in Canada.
  </p>

  <p>
    The answer is not a tariff argument or a political one. The answer is a purchasing decision. You vote with every order. When you choose local, you are choosing to sustain a manufacturing ecosystem in your community. When you choose Temu, you are choosing to dismantle it, one order at a time, in exchange for parts that will likely fail.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Look For in a Local 3D Printing Service</h2>

  <p>
    Not all local services are equal. Here is what separates a serious local fabricator from someone with a printer and a Shopify store.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Material selection.</strong> They should offer more than PLA. If a shop only has PLA and "PLA Plus," they are not equipped for anything beyond decorative or prototype work. A real fabricator runs ASA for outdoor and UV applications, PETG for utility parts, TPU for flexible components, and ideally carbon-fibre compounds for structural or load-bearing work.</li>
    <li><strong>Engineering knowledge.</strong> They should be able to recommend the correct material for your application without you having to know it in advance. If you say "I need a bracket for outside," they should immediately say "ASA or PETG-CF, here's why."</li>
    <li><strong>Accountability and iteration.</strong> Real makers reprint when something is wrong. They do not ghost you. They do not issue refund vouchers. They fix the part.</li>
    <li><strong>Transparency.</strong> They should be able to tell you exactly what they printed, at what settings, in what material, from which supplier. If they cannot tell you that, you have no way to know what you are getting.</li>
    <li><strong>Turnaround.</strong> A serious local shop turns orders in 24 to 72 hours. If the wait is two weeks, you are dealing with a hobbyist who is not running production capacity.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Broader Argument for Local Manufacturing</h2>

  <p>
    This argument extends well beyond 3D printing. Every category of product where local manufacturing is viable deserves the same analysis. What does the local option actually cost versus the total cost of the overseas option? What economic activity does the local purchase sustain? What disappears if the local option disappears?
  </p>

  <p>
    In fabrication specifically, there is an irreversibility problem. If a local machine shop closes because it could not compete with overseas pricing, the equipment is sold, the operator moves on, the institutional knowledge disperses. It does not come back. The next time a local business needs precision work, there is no one left to do it.
  </p>

  <p>
    3D printing is different from traditional machining in that the capital cost of entry is low. A maker can start with one printer and scale. The ecosystem can rebuild relatively quickly if there is demand to sustain it. But the demand has to come first. The infrastructure follows the orders.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why buying local is not a charity decision. It is an infrastructure decision. You are not paying a premium to feel good. You are paying a premium to keep the option available the next time you need it — and the time after that, when someone else in your community needs it too.
  </p>

